                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d457">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">812.00Sonora/573: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Consul at Ciudad Juarez</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Dye</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">El Paso, Tex</hi>
                        </placeName>., <date calendar="gregorian" when="1929-04-09T18:00:00-07:00"
                            >April 9, 1929—6 p.m.</date>
                        <lb/>[Received 9:37 p.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>Federals from Guadalupe on outskirts of Juarez but have agreed not to attack if
                    rebels leave. One train left for Casas Grandes about 4 p.m. Another train ready
                    to leave. In personal interview General Caraveo promised me to respect American
                    rights and added that there would be no fight unless the Federals came in and
                    attacked. Believe city will turn over peacefully as soon as Caraveo leaves.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Dye</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
